{{Infobox person | name = Shireen Mitchell | image = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[New York City]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Entrepreneur, author, technology analyst, diversity strategist | salary = | networth = | spouse = | children = | website = {{Official website|http://shireen.me}} }}
'''Shireen Mitchell''' is an American [[entrepreneur]], [[author]], technology analyst and diversity strategist. She founded Digital Sisters/Sistas, Inc.,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1484633 |title= Digital Gap Among Minority Children, Tavis Smiley Interviews Shireen Mitchell and Todd Oppenheimer, NPR}}</ref> the first organization dedicated to bringing women and girls of color online and Stop Online Violence Against Women (SOVAW),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blogher.com/brianna-wu-and-shireen-mitchell-life-online-target-gaming-community-blogher15 |title= What It’s Like to Be a Target on the Internet Every Day: Brianna Wu and Shireen Mitchell at #BlogHer15}}</ref> a project that addresses laws and policies to provide protections for women while online.
== Career == Shireen Mitchell began designing [[bulletin board systems]] and [[gopher (protocol)]] sites prior to the advent of websites. She was the webmaster for PoliticallyBlack.com, a site that was sold to Netivation (NTVN)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/netivationcom-signs-letter-of-intent-to-acquire-politicallyblackcom-76432277.html |title=Netivation.com Signs Letter of Intent to Acquire Politicallyblack.com}}</ref> a large media company as one of the web transactions in the late 1990s that later went public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasdaq.com/markets/ipos/filing.ashx?filingid=940456 |title=Netivation NASDAQ public offering}}</ref>
Mitchell formed the first woman of color web management firm in 1997, the Mitchell Holden Group (MHG). She then founded Digital Sisters/Sistas in 1999, first as a website and then an advocacy and training organization that focuses on [[technology]], [[new media]] and [[diversity (politics)|diversity]]. Digital Sisters was the first organization created specifically to help women and girls of color get into the STEM field and use technology in their daily lives.
In 2010, she formed Tech Media Swirl LLC, a digital social strategy company focused integrated media strategies for outreach to diverse communities. In 2013, she founded Stop Online Violence Against Women (SOVAW). The project highlights diverse voices of women, and in particular, women of color.
== Honors and awards == * Eelan Media, Top 100 Most Influential Black People on digital/social media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eelanmedia.com/top-100-most-influential-black-people-on-digitalsocial-media/ |title= Top 100 Most Influential Black People on digital/social media}}</ref> 2014 * DC Inno, Top Ten Influencers in Social Media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dcinno.streetwise.co/2012/03/27/dcs-top-ten-influencers-in-social-media/ |title=Top Ten Influencers in Social Media}}</ref> 2012 * Fast Company Most Influential Women in Tech,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3017137/women-in-tech-2010/the-most-influential-women-in-technology-2010-shireen-mitchell |title=Fast Company Most Influential Women in Tech}}</ref> 2010 * Washingtonian's Tech Titans,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2009/05/01/washingtons-tech-titans/ |title= Washingtonian's Tech Titans}}</ref> 2009 * The Root, 100 African-American Leaders of Excellence,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroot.com/articles/lists/2009/10/the_root_100_profiles/ |title=The Root 100 African-American Leaders of Excellence}}</ref> 2009
== Published works == * {{Cite book|ISBN=978-1-930722-45-3|date=21 June 2007|title=Gaining Daily Access to Science and Technology, ''50 Ways to Improve Women's Lives''|publisher=Inner Ocean Publishing}}
