'''''The Happy Hooker: My Own Story''''' is a best-selling [[memoir]] by [[Xaviera Hollander]], a [[call girl]], published in 1971. It sold over 20 million<ref>[http://www.philly.com/inquirer/magazine/20080626_Philmadelphia.html The Philadelphia Inquirer] on ''The Happy Hooker'': "He said he found it fascinating that her book, which has sold 20 million copies to date, is still being picked up today." (26 June 2008)</ref> copies.
[[Robin Moore]], who took Hollander's dictations of the book's contents, came up with the title, while Yvonne Dunleavy either transcribed the book<ref name=Hollander1971>{{Cite book |title=The Happy Hooker: My Own Story |publisher=Sphere Books |year=1971 |isbn=0-06-001416-4 |last=Hollander |first=Xaviera }}</ref> or ghostwrote it.<ref>John Cassidy, "The hell-raiser", ''Sydney Morning Herald'', 9 December 2000, Good Weekend, p. 80</ref>

== Adaptations ==
Hollander's book inspired a series of movies, starting with 1975's ''[[The Happy Hooker (film)|The Happy Hooker]],'' which starred [[Lynn Redgrave]].<ref name=IMDbHH1975>{{cite web|title=The Happy Hooker (1975)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0073091/|via=IMDb|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> The film was followed by two sequels: 1977's ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington]]''<ref name=IMDbHH1977>{{cite web|title=The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington (1977)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0076125/|via=IMDb|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> and 1980's ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes Hollywood]].''<ref name=IMDbHH1980>{{cite web|title=The Happy Hooker Goes Hollywood (1980)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0080839/|via=IMDb|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> In the sequels the role of Hollander was played by [[Joey Heatherton]] and [[Martine Beswick]] respectively.

